        "excerpt": "Jeroboam did not again recover strength in the days of Abijah; and the LORD struck him and he died.",
        "body": "The epilogue of the chapter (vv. 19-22) resolves the narrative on two tracks. On the military track, Abijah pursues Jeroboam and captures Bethel, Jeshanah, and Ephron with their villages (v. 19). The capture of Bethel is the Chronicler's sharpest irony. Bethel was the founding site of Jeroboam's golden calf — 1 Kings 12:28-29 records that he set one calf there and one in Dan, saying 'Here are your gods, O Israel, who brought you up from the land of Egypt.' The city that symbolized the northern kingdom's apostasy from the Davidic-Mosaic order now falls to the king who has just delivered the chapter's covenant speech defending that order. The theology is embodied in geography: the cult that could not save its devotees cannot save its capital.\n\nOn the theological track, vv. 20-21 place Jeroboam's decline and death in explicit contrast with Abijah's growth. Jeroboam 'did not again recover strength in the days of Abijah' — the battle was terminal for his dynasty's power. Then the Chronicler adds the judicial verdict: 'the LORD struck him and he died.' The same verb *nagaph* used for the battle rout (v. 15) now describes Jeroboam's personal end. The battle was not just a military defeat — it was the beginning of YHWH's judicial execution of the man who had set up golden calves and expelled the Levites. Jonathan Edwards would recognize the structure: God's patience with the wicked is not permanence; the blow struck against Jeroboam in battle continues until it reaches him personally.\n\nAbijah's power, by contrast, is expressed in the idiom of covenantal fruitfulness: fourteen wives, twenty-two sons, sixteen daughters (v. 21). This is not the Chronicler's endorsement of polygamy; it is his use of the ancient Near Eastern topos of fruitfulness as divine blessing — the same idiom that shapes Genesis 1:28 and the patriarchal narratives. The restraint of the closing verse (v. 22) is significant: Abijah's acts, ways, and words are recorded in the treatise of the prophet Iddo — a source outside the canon — and the Chronicler does not reproduce it. The chapter has never been about Abijah's personal sanctity. It has been about a covenant that holds even when its human beneficiaries are imperfect, a priesthood that functions even when the king is flawed, and a God who honors the reliance of a people even when their king would not pass the Kings' evaluation. The covenant of salt, not the character of the covenant's human beneficiaries, is the chapter's protagonist.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Midrash* (treatise, v. 22) — a term for an expository or interpretive composition; the Chronicler uses it here and in 2 Chronicles 24:27. The word shows that the Chronicler is working from and referencing other written sources, and is selecting theologically — not simply transcribing. *Chazaq* (grew strong, v. 21) — to become strong, prevail; the same root used of Rehoboam's sons in 2 Chronicles 11:17 and Hezekiah's strength in 32:7-8."
